Hercyniam silvam. A series of foreste and mountains, stretching from Helvetia to Hungary in a line parallel to the Danube, and described by Caesar (B. G. 6, 25), as nine day's journey in breadth and more than sixty in length. The name seems to be preserved in the modern Hartz Forest, which is however far less extensive.

Boihemi nomen. Compounded of Boii and heim (home of the Boii), now Bohemia. Heim—ham in the termination of so many names of towns, e. g. Framinglzam, Nottinglzam. The Boii were driven from their country by the Marcomanni, 42. The fugitives are supposed to have carried their name into Boioaria, now Bavaria. Of. Prichard's Physical Researches, Vol. 111.
